    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-02-06T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-02-06T08:00:00-05:00" n="78"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.5531/340: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Belgium</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brussels</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-02-06T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >February 6, 1935—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received February 6—11:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. At a meeting at Belgian Foreign Office yesterday afternoon at which Sussdorff
                    and Hughes<note n="19" xml:id="d78fn19">Thomas L. Hughes, Commercial Attaché in
                        Belgium.</note> were present as observers, representatives of General
                    Motors, Ford and Chrysler expressed satisfaction at offer of reduction on
                    automobile parts recently cabled to Belgian Embassy in Washington. The three
                    American companies which have assembly plants in Belgium are in substantial
                    accord with the Belgian Government regarding the new rates of duty on parts
                    including the labor safeguard clause. It developed at the meeting that the
                    American companies which do not have assembly plants in Belgium will derive no
                    benefit from the proposed reduction of duty on parts on account of the labor
                    safeguard clause. This fact undoubtedly lessens the importance of the
                    concessions which the Belgian Government is prepared to offer on parts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
